23
00:01:31,875 --> 00:01:35,799
not just a theme or a front end or a combat section.

24
00:01:36,599 --> 00:01:40,723
Everything was going to look like it was taking place in the pages of a comic book.

25
00:01:41,804 --> 00:01:45,007
How successful that was is up to you as an audience,

26
00:01:45,147 --> 00:01:50,051
but I was doing my best to try and make everything as comic book-like as possible.

27
00:01:51,853 --> 00:01:54,455
So you can see in these pages that the original idea...

28
00:01:55,294 --> 00:01:56,776
for the narrative side at least,

29
00:01:56,956 --> 00:01:59,499
because the gameplay didn't really change very much

30
00:01:59,559 --> 00:02:01,601
from what we intended from day one.

31
00:02:03,143 --> 00:02:06,806
However, the world and the feel of Void Bastards

32
00:02:07,227 --> 00:02:08,388
actually changed quite radically.

33
00:02:08,969 --> 00:02:10,390
So in these pages, you can see that

34
00:02:10,871 --> 00:02:15,376
the initial player character wasn't a series of prisoners.

35
00:02:15,556 --> 00:02:16,597
It was a single person.

36
00:02:17,599 --> 00:02:21,900
And the idea was that this person, when they died, would actually die,

37
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:26,421
but would be replicated back on what has become the Steve in Void Bastards.

38
00:02:26,461 --> 00:02:27,802
But we called it the Pod at the time.

39
00:02:28,782 --> 00:02:31,002
And every time this person was reincarnated,

40
00:02:31,022 --> 00:02:34,563
they would pick up photocopier-style errors.

41
00:02:35,363 --> 00:02:38,364
So a gauge of how successful you'd been at the end of the game

42
00:02:38,604 --> 00:02:42,145
was how genetically messed up this character had become over,

43
00:02:42,165 --> 00:02:45,966
you know, in between zero and hundreds of times of being resurrected.

44
00:02:47,092 --> 00:02:57,580
