00:06:30,802 --> 00:06:37,083
spaceships, so all of the wild colours that you see in the different ships, I was just

79
00:06:37,183 --> 00:06:40,884
using all at once, rather than trying to match them to particular things.

80
00:06:42,485 --> 00:06:46,005
So the next thing I would like to talk about is the way we develop the environments, which

81
00:06:46,025 --> 00:06:49,466
were very, very important, obviously, in the sort of game that Void Bastards is.

82
00:06:50,239 --> 00:06:53,542
We needed to make a lot of levels, but we needed to keep the scope very manageable,

83
00:06:54,203 --> 00:06:55,605
much as everything else in the game.

84
00:06:56,506 --> 00:07:00,571
Now, this is an area we couldn't economize quite as much as in other places,

85
00:07:00,711 --> 00:07:06,297
where, for example, the cutscenes, we decided to do them as largely still comic book images

86
00:07:06,397 --> 00:07:09,941
because it would fit with the theme, but also wouldn't require a lot of animation.

87
00:07:11,379 --> 00:07:12,980
With environments, we couldn't really do that.

88
00:07:13,141 --> 00:07:16,283
So we had to come up with a way to make the task manageable.

89
00:07:17,024 --> 00:07:21,228
And from my point of view, it felt to me to design an art style

90
00:07:21,288 --> 00:07:24,631
which didn't include tons and tons of detail

91
00:07:24,651 --> 00:07:26,873
that would be expensive or time consuming,

92
00:07:27,033 --> 00:07:29,615
which is the same thing, to create.

93
00:07:29,915 --> 00:07:34,980
So early on, we decided on a very open, thin line look.

94
00:07:36,622 --> 00:07:41,045
And I found the easiest way for me to pre-visualize this stuff was actually to use SketchUp,

95
00:07:41,806 --> 00:07:42,967
which is what you're seeing right now.

96
00:07:44,247 --> 00:07:48,490
And this had the advantage of being able to do little walkthrough animations for team members

97
00:07:48,530 --> 00:07:54,455
who weren't in the room with me that I could post and they could look at when they woke up in their time zone.

98
00:07:55,035 --> 00:07:59,538
And I found it very useful to be able to virtually walk around inside a space

99
00:07:59,859 --> 00:08:03,981
when it was still being concepted before anyone attempted to 3D model it.

100
00:08:04,947 --> 00:08:10,432
This is actually the first test that I could find that we did when we were still trying to decide

101
00:08:10,472 --> 00:08:16,537
whether or not we could make a 3D environment game with sprites, you know, in the old school

102
00:08:16,577 --> 00:08:23,083
manner of Outlaws and Duke Nukem that I'm very fond of. Concept being though that we could do

103
00:08:23,123 --> 00:08:27,006
that with high resolution textures that would look more like illustrations and less like

104
00:08:27,126 --> 00:08:28,788
pixelated 90s video games.

105
00:08:29,858 --> 00:08:33,360
And it was this clip that gave us the confidence to move forward.

106
00:08:33,701 --> 00:08:39,124
It's interesting to me here that you can see that the, already, the technology level and

107
00:08:39,144 --> 00:08:42,707
the look and feel was very different to what we wound up with in Void Bastards.

108
00:08:42,727 --> 00:08:50,212
We've got a very clean looking futuristic handgun, the enemies are very contemporary looking.

109
00:08:51,152 --> 00:08:55,896
The next step was to take this rough model and to do some paint over mock-ups of

110
00:08:56,016 --> 00:08:57,997
how the game might look when you were really playing it.

111
00:08:59,700 --> 00:09:04,924
Now these images are really interesting to me because it takes me back to when we hadn't

112
00:09:04,964 --> 00:09:09,166
really established a unique, what I would call a unique look for Void Bastards.

113
00:09:09,847 --> 00:09:14,670
A lot of this really does look like animation, which is, it is my background before getting

114
00:09:14,690 --> 00:09:15,290
into games.

